e":"1390–Overleden","1425":"1425","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1465":"1465","1442":"1442","1409":"1409","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England":"Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England","Bradford, Devonshire, England":"Bradford, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Powderham, Devon, England":"Powderham, Devon, England","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bradford, Holsworthy, Devonshire, England":"Bradford, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1390–":"1390–Deceased","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1410–1465":"1410–1465","1410–Male":"1410–Deceased","1425–Male":"1425–Deceased","1390–Female":"1390–Deceased","1425":"1425","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1465":"1465","1442":"1442","1409":"1409","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England":"Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England","Bradford, Devonshire, England":"Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Powderham, Devon, England":"Powderham, Devon, England","Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Bradford, Holsworthy, Devonshire, England":"Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Courtenay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Courtney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Courtney","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Courtenay near Sens in northern France, or some other place similarly named, from the name of a Gallo-Roman landlord, <i>Curtenus</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘short’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","Irish: English surname adopted for <b>Ó Curnáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Curnán’</i>, an Old Irish personal name based on a diminutive of <i>corn</i> ‘horn’.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Athon de Courtenay, who lived in Courtenay in Loiret in the early 11th century. Renaud de Courtenay held land in Devon in the 12th century, and the family later held the title of Earls of Devon following the marriage of Hugh de Courtenay to Margaret de Bohun, granddaughter of King Edward I, in 1325."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":65,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Ann Margaret Courtenay was born in 1390, in Powderham, Devon, England. She married William de Peverell V in 1409, in Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1390–":"1390–Surnud","1380–1442":"1380–1442","1410–1465":"1410–1465","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1425":"1425","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1465":"1465","1442":"1442","1409":"1409","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England":"Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England","Bradford, Devonshire, England":"Bradford, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Powderham